### 6.2 Terms & definitions

#### Null Hypothesis and Alternative Hypothesis

Are we testing for (a) any change/difference from the (assumed) population mean \(\mu_{0}\), or (b)/(c) a definite increase/decrease in the (assumed) population mean?

**Null hypothesis** (denoted by \(H_{0}\))

\(H_{0}\) is a statement that says that a **population parameter** takes a **specific value**.

**Alternative hypothesis** (denoted by \(H_{1}\))

\(H_{1}\) is a statement that says that the population parameter takes a value different, in some way, from the value given in \(H_{0}\).

\begin{tabular}{l l} Test & \(H_{0}:\mu=\mu_{0}\) (Assumption: population mean is \(\mu_{0}\)) \\ vs. & (a) \(H_{1}:\mu\neq\mu_{0}\) (b) \(H_{1}:\mu>\mu_{0}\) (c) \(H_{1}:\mu<\mu_{0}\) \\ \end{tabular}

\begin{tabular}{l l} \hline In a two-tailed test, \\ \(H_{1}\) looks for any change in the population \\ mean (can be increase or decrease). \\ \end{tabular}

Note:

1. The rejection of the null hypothesis will generally imply that the alternative hypothesis is accepted. In this case, we conclude that the null hypothesis is false.
2. Failure to reject the null hypothesis is not the same as accepting the null hypothesis. It only means there is insufficient statistical evidence to reject \(H_{0}\) in favour of \(H_{1}\) (i.e. \(H_{0}\) may or may not be true). In other words, **we cannot conclude that we accept \(H_{0}\)**.

#### 6.2.2 Test Statistic

The sample statistic used to test the hypotheses is called the **test statistic**. In the H1 Maths syllabus, we take the sample mean \(\overline{X}\) and _standardise_ it to obtain the standard normal distribution \(Z\). In this way, any particular value \(\overline{x}\) will have a corresponding standard score (also known as \(z\)-score), which is a measure of its number of standard deviations above or below \(\mu\). Recall that if we use a large sample size \(n\), then \(\overline{X}\) approximately follows a normal distribution by Central Limit Theorem (CLT), so a bell curve appears!

If we now assume our null hypothesis is true, then we get something familiar:

\[\mbox{Under }H_{0}\,,\ \overline{X}\sim\mbox{N}\!\left(\mu,\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n} \right)\mbox{ and so }Z=\frac{\overline{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\sim\mbox{N}(0,1)\,.\]

Note:

1. If the population \(X\) is already normal, then Central Limit Theorem is not required.
2. If \(\sigma^{2}\) is unknown, we use the unbiased estimate \(s^{2}\) (\(S^{2}_{x}\) in GC) instead.

\[s^{2}=\frac{\dot{n}}{n-1}\!\left(\frac{\Sigma(x-\overline{x})^{2}}{n}\right) \!\!=\!\frac{1}{n-1}\!\left(\Sigma x^{2}-\frac{(\Sigma x)^{2}}{n}\right)\ \ =\frac{n}{n-1}\!\times\!\mbox{sample variance}\]

